Home of the Day
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    Desirable Hill Country Acreage Living                




See All Homes of the Day





 











 Enlarge





                From left, Pemex Logistics CEO Ignacio Aguilar Alvarez and Tesoro Corp. Executive Vice… more 

                Petroleos Mexicanos            








 



San Antonio-based refining company Tesoro Corp. (NYSE: TSO) has inked a historic transportation and storage deal in Mexico.
Tesoro Executive Vice President Keith Casey flew to Mexico City, where he signed a three-year deal with Pemex Logistics CEO Ignacio Aguilar Alvarez on Tuesday afternoon.













 Enlarge






                            From left, Pemex Logistics CEO Ignacio Aguilar Alvarez and Tesoro Corp. Executive Vice… more 
Petroleos Mexicanos










 


Under the terms of the deal, Tesoro will now be able to use refined product pipelines and storage terminals owned by Pemex Logistics in the states of Baja California and Sonora.




In May, Tesoro beat 21 other companies in a Pemex Logistics auction, in which the San Antonio-based company was reported to have offered the best tariffs to obtain capacity on the pipeline and storage terminal network.
Facing sagging production from six aging refineries, Mexico enacted historic energy reforms in late 2014, opening its market to foreign investment and competition. Touted as the first auction for Pemex Logistics, the reforms allow foreign companies such as Tesoro to sell gasoline, diesel and other refined products in Mexico.
Tesoro CEO Greg Goff said in a statement that the deal will boost the retail side of the refining company's business. The San Antonio-based refining company plans to sell gasoline and diesel in Mexico under its ARCO brand.
"The expansion of our strategic footprint to include Northern Mexico strengthens our integrated value chain with significant growth opportunities for our marketing business," Goff said in his statement. "We are excited about Mexico and the opportunity to create value for the company, customers, business partners and communities."




 


With refineries in El Paso and the Los Angeles area, the agreement with Pemex Logistics gives Tesoro capacity on pipelines linking cities such as Mexicali, Rosarito, Ensenada, Guayamas, Hermosillo and Ciudad Obregon. It also gives the refiner storage terminal space in Rosarito, Mexicali, Ensenada, Guaymas, Ciudad Obregón, Hermosillo, Magdalena, Nogales and Navojoa.
Pemex Logistics is expected to hold a second auction for capacity on its network this year.

Sergio Chapa covers manufacturing and the energy industry











